<p>On my migration from Github Pages to Cloudflare for free static
      hosting that includes some minimal server-side analytics<br /></p><h2
      style="text-align: left;">Backstory<br /></h2><p>For some time now
      (narrator: <a href="https://twitter.sheetsj.com/236431644083499008/">apparently 11
      years</a>, wow!) I've run a small side project at <a
      href="https://gaspumpr.com/">gaspumpr.com</a> to help calculate the cheapest gas to
      buy for my car that accepts up to E85. It is a super lite "app" (<a
      href="https://github.com/jeffsheets/GasPumpr.com/">github source</a>), just some html
      + css + a tiny sprinkle of javascript to do some minor calculations, published to a Github
      Pages free static site.</p><div style="text-align: center;"><img
      alt="gaspumpr.com screenshot" height="238"
      src="data:image/png;base64,"
      width="400" /></div><p></p><p>I enjoy minorly tracking the page
      hits just to get a feeling for how much usage it gets (not much) but also to see occasional
      spikes and go figure out why. (Like that time the <a
      href="https://twitter.sheetsj.com/1155990117925810182/">governor of Nebraska used
      it</a> to promote their agenda without realizing the calculations kind of defeated their
      own idea, but hey any publicity is good publicity! Or when the <a
      href="https://twitter.sheetsj.com/926265045906001921/">NE Corn Board published it</a>
      without reaching out)</p><p style="text-align: center;"><img alt="Tweets about
      the NE Corn Board and Governor sharing gaspumpr.com" height="313"
      src="data:image/png;base64,"
      width="400" /> <br /></p><h2 style="text-align: left;">Static Site
      Options</h2><div style="text-align: left;"><p>Until recently, I used Google
      Analytics to collect the hit counts.
      Back 11 years ago it seemed pretty great to get in depth stats so
      easily, even if they were client-side collected. Jump ahead though and I
      don't like the client-side tracking piece for reasons.</p><p>So I went
      out looking for free Static Site (aka HTML/CSS/JS, aka Jamstack, aka
      boring website) hosting solutions that provided minimal serverside
      analytics.</p><h3 style="text-align: left;">Github Pages</h3><p
      style="text-align: left;">For years it has worked like a charm, but after a quick search,
      Github Pages does not provide any server-side hit counting stats. Any solution would require a
      3rd party client-side library.</p><h3 style="text-align:
      left;">Surge.sh</h3><p style="text-align: left;">My goto testing/demo site
      publishing mechanism is <a href="https://surge.sh/">surge.sh</a>. It is great --
      seriously check it out! npm publish a site in seconds. But nothing to track server-side stats,
      so the search continued.</p><h3 style="text-align: left;">Other
      options</h3><p style="text-align: left;">I stumbled upon this great <a
      href="https://www.codejam.info/2021/09/free-static-hosting-server-side-analytics.html">Free
      static hosting with server-side analytics</a> blog post from <a
      href="https://www.codejam.info/val.html">Val</a> in 2021 that includes a few other
      options in the category, including Netlify, Render, Google Cloud, and Vercel. Val gives a
      great description of using a combination of Vercel + Google Cloud VMs logging integrations.
      This approach seems to fit well, however being my lazy self I was looking for an even simpler
      solution...</p><h3 style="text-align: left;">Cloudflare</h3><p
      style="text-align: left;">To think I'd end up at Cloudflare is more than surprising to me.
      I think of Cloudflare as the "enterprise" CDN solution, which they definitely are. But somehow
      I never noticed their solo developer solutions and free pricing tier!</p><p
      style="text-align: left;"><b><a href="https://pages.cloudflare.com/">Cloudflare
      Pages</a></b> -- is basically their Github Pages clone. Point it at your github
      repo and it'll build and deploy. Worked easily for my gaspumpr HTML site. They also handle
      minor build steps for the various popular javascript frameworks.</p><p
      style="text-align: left;"><b><a
      href="https://www.cloudflare.com/application-services/products/cdn/">Cloudflare
      CDN</a></b> (DNS + ReverseProxy) -- this is what you normally think of for
      Cloudflare. The CDN fronts your site as a caching layer, and as such can provide minimal stat
      analytics from the server-side, exactly what I was looking for! And surprisingly free for
      small projects!</p><p style="text-align: center;"><img alt="24 hour Stat graphs
      from Cloudflare for gaspumpr.com" height="271"
      src="data:image/png;base64,"
      width="400" />&nbsp;</p><h2 style="text-align: left;">Migration from Github
      Pages to Cloudflare</h2><p style="text-align: left;">This was broken down to a few
      steps for me. Your journey would be similar though each setup is so unique I'm sure there
      could be small differences and side quests along the way.</p><ul style="text-align:
      left;"><li style="text-align: left;">Publish to Cloudflare Pages <br
      /></li><ul><li style="text-align: left;">Setup/cleanup the <a
      href="https://github.com/jeffsheets/GasPumpr.com">git
      repo</a></li><ul><li style="text-align: left;">I wanted to publish
      from a `main` branch instead of the `gh-pages` branch, so did a little branch reconfiguring
      here.</li><li style="text-align: left;">Remove the CNAME file. I think I had the
      cname file to get the custom domain name working on github pages. After some trial and error I
      realized it was causing cloudflare deploy to not show up.</li></ul><li
      style="text-align: left;">Link Github in Cloudflare pages
      dashboard</li><ul><li style="text-align: left;">Just a couple clicks to
      point at the github branch, and a build and deploy kicks off and
      publishes!</li></ul><li style="text-align: left;">Setup custom domain in
      cloudflare dashboard</li><ul><li style="text-align: left;">It listed the
      small steps needed to update my domain name provider with DNS entries for
      Cloudflare</li><li style="text-align: left;">Took a few minutes for DNS caches to
      reset then gaspumpr.com was back up and live</li></ul></ul><li
      style="text-align: left;">Setup Cloudflare CDN</li><ul><li
      style="text-align: left;">In the Websites section of the Cloudflare dashboard, setup a few
      config things to point to gaspumpr.com.&nbsp;</li><li style="text-align:
      left;">This was pretty simple since Cloudflare Pages was already hosting the
      site.</li><li style="text-align: left;">Note: I could have kept everything on
      Github Pages and simply pointed the CDN in front. However it seemed so easy to just move over
      to Cloudflare pages that I didn't even look into it
      much.</li></ul></ul><h2 style="text-align: left;">Wrap</h2><p
      style="text-align: left;">That's it! 15 minutes of setup and now I have beautiful
      server-side non-intrusive stats to view whenever I please, and no client-side JS library was
      needed in the process.</p><p style="text-align: left;">Cloudflare CDN + Pages for
      the win <br /></p><p style="text-align: left;"><br /></p><p
      style="text-align: left;"></p></div>
